  • Constructor Details

    • PPRamseteCommand

      public PPRamseteCommand(PathPlannerTrajectory trajectory, Supplier<edu.wpi.first.math.geometry.Pose2d> poseSupplier, edu.wpi.first.math.controller.RamseteController controller, edu.wpi.first.math.controller.SimpleMotorFeedforward feedforward, edu.wpi.first.math.kinematics.DifferentialDriveKinematics kinematics, Supplier<edu.wpi.first.math.kinematics.DifferentialDriveWheelSpeeds> speedsSupplier, edu.wpi.first.math.controller.PIDController leftController, edu.wpi.first.math.controller.PIDController rightController, BiConsumer<Double,Double> outputVolts, boolean useAllianceColor, edu.wpi.first.wpilibj2.command.Subsystem... requirements)
      Constructs a new PPRamseteCommand that, when executed, will follow the provided trajectory. PID control and feedforward are handled internally, and outputs are scaled -12 to 12 representing units of volts.

      Note: The controller will *not* set the outputVolts to zero upon completion of the path - this is left to the user, since it is not appropriate for paths with nonstationary endstates.

      Parameters:
      trajectory - The trajectory to follow.
      poseSupplier - A function that supplies the robot pose - use one of the odometry classes to provide this.
      controller - The RAMSETE controller used to follow the trajectory.
      feedforward - The feedforward to use for the drive.
      kinematics - The kinematics for the robot drivetrain.
      speedsSupplier - A function that supplies the speeds of the left and right sides of the robot drive.
      leftController - The PIDController for the left side of the robot drive.
      rightController - The PIDController for the right side of the robot drive.
      outputVolts - A function that consumes the computed left and right outputs (in volts) for the robot drive.
      useAllianceColor - Should the path states be automatically transformed based on alliance color? In order for this to work properly, you MUST create your path on the blue side of the field.
      requirements - The subsystems to require.

    • PPRamseteCommand

      public PPRamseteCommand(PathPlannerTrajectory trajectory, Supplier<edu.wpi.first.math.geometry.Pose2d> poseSupplier, edu.wpi.first.math.controller.RamseteController controller, edu.wpi.first.math.kinematics.DifferentialDriveKinematics kinematics, BiConsumer<Double,Double> outputMetersPerSecond, boolean useAllianceColor, edu.wpi.first.wpilibj2.command.Subsystem... requirements)
      Constructs a new PPRamseteCommand that, when executed, will follow the provided trajectory. Performs no PID control and calculates no feedforwards; outputs are the raw wheel speeds from the RAMSETE controller, and will need to be converted into a usable form by the user.
      Parameters:
      trajectory - The trajectory to follow.
      poseSupplier - A function that supplies the robot pose - use one of the odometry classes to provide this.
      controller - The RAMSETE follower used to follow the trajectory.
      kinematics - The kinematics for the robot drivetrain.
      outputMetersPerSecond - A function that consumes the computed left and right wheel speeds.
      useAllianceColor - Should the path states be automatically transformed based on alliance color? In order for this to work properly, you MUST create your path on the blue side of the field.
      requirements - The subsystems to require.

      public static void setLoggingCallbacks(Consumer<PathPlannerTrajectory> logActiveTrajectory, Consumer<edu.wpi.first.math.geometry.Pose2d> logTargetPose, Consumer<edu.wpi.first.math.kinematics.ChassisSpeeds> logSetpoint, BiConsumer<edu.wpi.first.math.geometry.Translation2d,edu.wpi.first.math.geometry.Rotation2d> logError)
      Set custom logging callbacks for this command to use instead of the default configuration of pushing values to SmartDashboard
      Parameters:
      logActiveTrajectory - Consumer that accepts a PathPlannerTrajectory representing the active path. This will be called whenever a PPRamseteCommand starts
      logTargetPose - Consumer that accepts a Pose2d representing the target pose while path following
      logSetpoint - Consumer that accepts a ChassisSpeeds object representing the setpoint speeds
      logError - BiConsumer that accepts a Translation2d and Rotation2d representing the error while path following
